The paper discusses decision tree learning algorithms and their theoretical guarantees, which are typically studied in the machine learning (cs.LG) and data structures (cs.DS) communities. The paper also analyzes the complexity of decision trees, which falls under the computational complexity (cs.CC) category. The use of heuristics and the analysis of their limitations suggests a focus on artificial intelligence (cs.AI). Finally, the mention of sample and memory complexity suggests a possible connection to information theory (cs.IT).
